t2572.text: (I’d just like to point out it was three different dresses too, so no fucking way this lady was just critical of my laziness)

t2573.text: Another week or two passed and I was walking through the grounds of my alma mater minor & estranged employer {university name withheld for pseudo-legal reasons (it rhymes with ‘sydney’)} & was vaguely aware of disapproval wafting by. Again I was in a dress...

t2574.text: Yes, you guessed it - same woman.

t2575.text: Couple of weeks later I passed someone on King street who made little vomiting noises as they passed. I looked up and thought she looked vaguely familiar, then looked down and noticed I happened to be wearing a dress (contrary to my publicists, I don’t *always*).

t2576.text: I did my best pantomime pose and replied “I know!”, and she was like “ You look ridiculous” in a really spiteful tone. So perhaps somewhat cruelly I smilingly said “so do you!” and kept going (in fact both of us barely stopped walking by during this exchange)

t6478.text: Others may feel differently, and that's their call. That's why I'm going to support my family. Cause they've come down on a different side of the fence.

t6479.text: I don't think you can til you're staring at it. Where I'm going today is not where my dad is. It's were what's left of the bag of meat he piloted around is, sure. But he is not there.

t6480.text: .. As they rasp out "I don't want to go" through cancerous lungs and poisoned blood. That's trauma. I've come to deal with the idea of mortality. I've considered it, read about it. Fallen into some philosophy about it. I won't sya I've come to terms with it, though.

t6481.text: Today I'll be standing in support of my stepmother as she visits her husband, and my father's, grave for the first time in years. She's having a hard time with the idea, and understandably so. Can't imagine anything worse than holding someone you love..
